    36→/**
    37→ * <p>The sticky assignor serves two purposes. First, it guarantees an assignment that is as balanced as possible, meaning either:
    38→ * <ul>
    39→ * <li>the numbers of topic partitions assigned to consumers differ by at most one; or</li>
    40→ * <li>each consumer that has 2+ fewer topic partitions than some other consumer cannot get any of those topic partitions transferred to it.</li>
    41→ * </ul>
    42→ * Second, it preserved as many existing assignment as possible when a reassignment occurs. This helps in saving some of the
    43→ * overhead processing when topic partitions move from one consumer to another.</p>
    44→ *
    45→ * <p>Starting fresh it would work by distributing the partitions over consumers as evenly as possible. Even though this may sound similar to
    46→ * how round robin assignor works, the second example below shows that it is not.
    47→ * During a reassignment it would perform the reassignment in such a way that in the new assignment
    48→ * <ol>
    49→ * <li>topic partitions are still distributed as evenly as possible, and</li>
    50→ * <li>topic partitions stay with their previously assigned consumers as much as possible.</li>
    51→ * </ol>
    52→ * Of course, the first goal above takes precedence over the second one.</p>
    53→ *
    54→ * <p><b>Example 1.</b> Suppose there are three consumers <code>C0</code>, <code>C1</code>, <code>C2</code>,
    55→ * four topics <code>t0,</code> <code>t1</code>, <code>t2</code>, <code>t3</code>, and each topic has 2 partitions,
    56→ * resulting in partitions <code>t0p0</code>, <code>t0p1</code>, <code>t1p0</code>, <code>t1p1</code>, <code>t2p0</code>,
    57→ * <code>t2p1</code>, <code>t3p0</code>, <code>t3p1</code>. Each consumer is subscribed to all three topics.
    58→ *
    59→ * The assignment with both sticky and round robin assignors will be:
    60→ * <ul>
    61→ * <li><code>C0: [t0p0, t1p1, t3p0]</code></li>
    62→ * <li><code>C1: [t0p1, t2p0, t3p1]</code></li>
    63→ * <li><code>C2: [t1p0, t2p1]</code></li>
    64→ * </ul>
    65→ *
    66→ * Now, let's assume <code>C1</code> is removed and a reassignment is about to happen. The round robin assignor would produce:
    67→ * <ul>
    68→ * <li><code>C0: [t0p0, t1p0, t2p0, t3p0]</code></li>
    69→ * <li><code>C2: [t0p1, t1p1, t2p1, t3p1]</code></li>
    70→ * </ul>
    71→ *
    72→ * while the sticky assignor would result in:
    73→ * <ul>
    74→ * <li><code>C0 [t0p0, t1p1, t3p0, t2p0]</code></li>
    75→ * <li><code>C2 [t1p0, t2p1, t0p1, t3p1]</code></li>
    76→ * </ul>
    77→ * preserving all the previous assignments (unlike the round robin assignor).
    78→ *</p>
    79→ * <p><b>Example 2.</b> There are three consumers <code>C0</code>, <code>C1</code>, <code>C2</code>,
    80→ * and three topics <code>t0</code>, <code>t1</code>, <code>t2</code>, with 1, 2, and 3 partitions respectively.
    81→ * Therefore, the partitions are <code>t0p0</code>, <code>t1p0</code>, <code>t1p1</code>, <code>t2p0</code>,
    82→ * <code>t2p1</code>, <code>t2p2</code>. <code>C0</code> is subscribed to <code>t0</code>; <code>C1</code> is subscribed to
    83→ * <code>t0</code>, <code>t1</code>; and <code>C2</code> is subscribed to <code>t0</code>, <code>t1</code>, <code>t2</code>.
    84→ *
    85→ * The round robin assignor would come up with the following assignment:
    86→ * <ul>
    87→ * <li><code>C0 [t0p0]</code></li>
    88→ * <li><code>C1 [t1p0]</code></li>
    89→ * <li><code>C2 [t1p1, t2p0, t2p1, t2p2]</code></li>
    90→ * </ul>
    91→ *
    92→ * which is not as balanced as the assignment suggested by sticky assignor:
    93→ * <ul>
    94→ * <li><code>C0 [t0p0]</code></li>
    95→ * <li><code>C1 [t1p0, t1p1]</code></li>
    96→ * <li><code>C2 [t2p0, t2p1, t2p2]</code></li>
    97→ * </ul>
    98→ *
    99→ * Now, if consumer <code>C0</code> is removed, these two assignors would produce the following assignments.
   100→ * Round Robin (preserves 3 partition assignments):
   101→ * <ul>
   102→ * <li><code>C1 [t0p0, t1p1]</code></li>
   103→ * <li><code>C2 [t1p0, t2p0, t2p1, t2p2]</code></li>
   104→ * </ul>
   105→ *
   106→ * Sticky (preserves 5 partition assignments):
   107→ * <ul>
   108→ * <li><code>C1 [t1p0, t1p1, t0p0]</code></li>
   109→ * <li><code>C2 [t2p0, t2p1, t2p2]</code></li>
   110→ * </ul>
   111→ *</p>
   112→ * <h3>Impact on <code>ConsumerRebalanceListener</code></h3>
   113→ * The sticky assignment strategy can provide some optimization to those consumers that have some partition cleanup code
   114→ * in their <code>onPartitionsRevoked()</code> callback listeners. The cleanup code is placed in that callback listener
   115→ * because the consumer has no assumption or hope of preserving any of its assigned partitions after a rebalance when it
   116→ * is using range or round robin assignor. The listener code would look like this:
   117→ * <pre>
   118→ * {@code
   119→ * class TheOldRebalanceListener implements ConsumerRebalanceListener {
   120→ *
   121→ *   void onPartitionsRevoked(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
   122→ *     for (TopicPartition partition: partitions) {
   123→ *       commitOffsets(partition);
   124→ *       cleanupState(partition);
   125→ *     }
   126→ *   }
   127→ *
   128→ *   void onPartitionsAssigned(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
   129→ *     for (TopicPartition partition: partitions) {
   130→ *       initializeState(partition);
   131→ *       initializeOffset(partition);
   132→ *     }
   133→ *   }
   134→ * }
   135→ * }
   136→ * </pre>
   137→ *
   138→ * As mentioned above, one advantage of the sticky assignor is that, in general, it reduces the number of partitions that
   139→ * actually move from one consumer to another during a reassignment. Therefore, it allows consumers to do their cleanup
   140→ * more efficiently. Of course, they still can perform the partition cleanup in the <code>onPartitionsRevoked()</code>
   141→ * listener, but they can be more efficient and make a note of their partitions before and after the rebalance, and do the
   142→ * cleanup after the rebalance only on the partitions they have lost (which is normally not a lot). The code snippet below
   143→ * clarifies this point:
   144→ * <pre>
   145→ * {@code
   146→ * class TheNewRebalanceListener implements ConsumerRebalanceListener {
   147→ *   Collection<TopicPartition> lastAssignment = Collections.emptyList();
   148→ *
   149→ *   void onPartitionsRevoked(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
   150→ *     for (TopicPartition partition: partitions)
   151→ *       commitOffsets(partition);
   152→ *   }
   153→ *
   154→ *   void onPartitionsAssigned(Collection<TopicPartition> assignment) {
   155→ *     for (TopicPartition partition: difference(lastAssignment, assignment))
   156→ *       cleanupState(partition);
   157→ *
   158→ *     for (TopicPartition partition: difference(assignment, lastAssignment))
   159→ *       initializeState(partition);
   160→ *
   161→ *     for (TopicPartition partition: assignment)
   162→ *       initializeOffset(partition);
   163→ *
   164→ *     this.lastAssignment = assignment;
   165→ *   }
   166→ * }
   167→ * }
   168→ * </pre>
   169→ *
   170→ * Any consumer that uses sticky assignment can leverage this listener like this:
   171→ * <code>consumer.subscribe(topics, new TheNewRebalanceListener());</code>
   172→ *
   173→ * Note that you can leverage the {@link CooperativeStickyAssignor} so that only partitions which are being
   174→ * reassigned to another consumer will be revoked. That is the preferred assignor for newer cluster. See
   175→ * {@link ConsumerPartitionAssignor.RebalanceProtocol} for a detailed explanation of cooperative rebalancing.
   176→ */
   177→public class StickyAssignor extends AbstractStickyAssignor {
   178→    public static final String STICKY_ASSIGNOR_NAME = "sticky";
   179→
   180→    // these schemas are used for preserving consumer's previously assigned partitions
   181→    // list and sending it as user data to the leader during a rebalance
   182→    static final String TOPIC_PARTITIONS_KEY_NAME = "previous_assignment";
   183→    static final String TOPIC_KEY_NAME = "topic";
   184→    static final String PARTITIONS_KEY_NAME = "partitions";
   185→    private static final String GENERATION_KEY_NAME = "generation";
   186→
   187→    static final Schema TOPIC_ASSIGNMENT = new Schema(
   188→        new Field(TOPIC_KEY_NAME, Type.STRING),
   189→        new Field(PARTITIONS_KEY_NAME, new ArrayOf(Type.INT32)));
   190→    static final Schema STICKY_ASSIGNOR_USER_DATA_V0 = new Schema(
   191→        new Field(TOPIC_PARTITIONS_KEY_NAME, new ArrayOf(TOPIC_ASSIGNMENT)));
   192→    private static final Schema STICKY_ASSIGNOR_USER_DATA_V1 = new Schema(
   193→        new Field(TOPIC_PARTITIONS_KEY_NAME, new ArrayOf(TOPIC_ASSIGNMENT)),
   194→        new Field(GENERATION_KEY_NAME, Type.INT32));
   195→
   196→    private List<TopicPartition> memberAssignment = null;
   197→    private int generation = DEFAULT_GENERATION; // consumer group generation
   198→
   199→    @Override
   200→    public String name() {
   201→        return STICKY_ASSIGNOR_NAME;
   202→    }
   203→
   204→    @Override
   205→    public void onAssignment(Assignment assignment, ConsumerGroupMetadata metadata) {
   206→        memberAssignment = assignment.partitions();
   207→        this.generation = metadata.generationId();
   208→    }
   209→
   210→    @Override
   211→    public ByteBuffer subscriptionUserData(Set<String> topics) {
   212→        if (memberAssignment == null)
