    31→/**
    32→ * <p>The round robin assignor lays out all the available partitions and all the available consumers. It
    33→ * then proceeds to do a round robin assignment from partition to consumer. If the subscriptions of all consumer
    34→ * instances are identical, then the partitions will be uniformly distributed. (i.e., the partition ownership counts
    35→ * will be within a delta of exactly one across all consumers.)
    36→ *
    37→ * <p>For example, suppose there are two consumers <code>C0</code> and <code>C1</code>, two topics <code>t0</code> and <code>t1</code>,
    38→ * and each topic has 3 partitions, resulting in partitions <code>t0p0</code>, <code>t0p1</code>, <code>t0p2</code>,
    39→ * <code>t1p0</code>, <code>t1p1</code>, and <code>t1p2</code>.
    40→ *
    41→ * <p>The assignment will be:
    42→ * <ul>
    43→ * <li><code>C0: [t0p0, t0p2, t1p1]</code>
    44→ * <li><code>C1: [t0p1, t1p0, t1p2]</code>
    45→ * </ul>
    46→ *
    47→ * <p>When subscriptions differ across consumer instances, the assignment process still considers each
    48→ * consumer instance in round robin fashion but skips over an instance if it is not subscribed to
    49→ * the topic. Unlike the case when subscriptions are identical, this can result in imbalanced
    50→ * assignments. For example, we have three consumers <code>C0</code>, <code>C1</code>, <code>C2</code>,
    51→ * and three topics <code>t0</code>, <code>t1</code>, <code>t2</code>, with 1, 2, and 3 partitions, respectively.
    52→ * Therefore, the partitions are <code>t0p0</code>, <code>t1p0</code>, <code>t1p1</code>, <code>t2p0</code>, <code>t2p1</code>, <code>t2p2</code>.
    53→ * <code>C0</code> is subscribed to <code>t0</code>;
    54→ * <code>C1</code> is subscribed to <code>t0</code>, <code>t1</code>;
    55→ * and <code>C2</code> is subscribed to <code>t0</code>, <code>t1</code>, <code>t2</code>.
    56→ *
    57→ * <p>That assignment will be:
    58→ * <ul>
    59→ * <li><code>C0: [t0p0]</code>
    60→ * <li><code>C1: [t1p0]</code>
    61→ * <li><code>C2: [t1p1, t2p0, t2p1, t2p2]</code>
    62→ * </ul>
    63→ *
    64→ * Since the introduction of static membership, we could leverage <code>group.instance.id</code> to make the assignment behavior more sticky.
    65→ * For example, we have three consumers with assigned <code>member.id</code> <code>C0</code>, <code>C1</code>, <code>C2</code>,
    66→ * two topics <code>t0</code> and <code>t1</code>, and each topic has 3 partitions, resulting in partitions <code>t0p0</code>,
    67→ * <code>t0p1</code>, <code>t0p2</code>, <code>t1p0</code>, <code>t1p1</code>, and <code>t1p2</code>. We choose to honor
    68→ * the sorted order based on ephemeral <code>member.id</code>.
    69→ *
    70→ * <p>The assignment will be:
    71→ * <ul>
    72→ * <li><code>C0: [t0p0, t1p0]</code>
    73→ * <li><code>C1: [t0p1, t1p1]</code>
    74→ * <li><code>C2: [t0p2, t1p2]</code>
    75→ * </ul>
    76→ *
    77→ * After one rolling bounce, group coordinator will attempt to assign new <code>member.id</code> towards consumers,
    78→ * for example <code>C0</code> -&gt; <code>C5</code> <code>C1</code> -&gt; <code>C3</code>, <code>C2</code> -&gt; <code>C4</code>.
    79→ *
    80→ * <p>The assignment could be completely shuffled to:
    81→ * <ul>
    82→ * <li><code>C3 (was C1): [t0p0, t1p0] (before was [t0p1, t1p1])</code>
    83→ * <li><code>C4 (was C2): [t0p1, t1p1] (before was [t0p2, t1p2])</code>
    84→ * <li><code>C5 (was C0): [t0p2, t1p2] (before was [t0p0, t1p0])</code>
    85→ * </ul>
    86→ *
    87→ * This issue could be mitigated by the introduction of static membership. Consumers will have individual instance ids
    88→ * <code>I1</code>, <code>I2</code>, <code>I3</code>. As long as
    89→ * 1. Number of members remain the same across generation
    90→ * 2. Static members' identities persist across generation
    91→ * 3. Subscription pattern doesn't change for any member
    92→ *
    93→ * <p>The assignment will always be:
    94→ * <ul>
    95→ * <li><code>I0: [t0p0, t1p0]</code>
    96→ * <li><code>I1: [t0p1, t1p1]</code>
    97→ * <li><code>I2: [t0p2, t1p2]</code>
    98→ * </ul>
    99→ */
   100→public class RoundRobinAssignor extends AbstractPartitionAssignor {
   101→    public static final String ROUNDROBIN_ASSIGNOR_NAME = "roundrobin";
   102→
   103→    @Override
   104→    public Map<String, List<TopicPartition>> assign(Map<String, Integer> partitionsPerTopic,
   105→                                                    Map<String, Subscription> subscriptions) {
   106→        Map<String, List<TopicPartition>> assignment = new HashMap<>();
   107→        List<MemberInfo> memberInfoList = new ArrayList<>();
   108→        for (Map.Entry<String, Subscription> memberSubscription : subscriptions.entrySet()) {
   109→            assignment.put(memberSubscription.getKey(), new ArrayList<>());
   110→            memberInfoList.add(new MemberInfo(memberSubscription.getKey(),
   111→                                              memberSubscription.getValue().groupInstanceId()));
   112→        }
   113→
   114→        CircularIterator<MemberInfo> assigner = new CircularIterator<>(Utils.sorted(memberInfoList));
   115→
   116→        for (TopicPartition partition : allPartitionsSorted(partitionsPerTopic, subscriptions)) {
   117→            final String topic = partition.topic();
   118→            while (!subscriptions.get(assigner.peek().memberId).topics().contains(topic))
   119→                assigner.next();
   120→            assignment.get(assigner.next().memberId).add(partition);
   121→        }
   122→        return assignment;
   123→    }
   124→
   125→    private List<TopicPartition> allPartitionsSorted(Map<String, Integer> partitionsPerTopic,
   126→                                                     Map<String, Subscription> subscriptions) {
   127→        SortedSet<String> topics = new TreeSet<>();
   128→        for (Subscription subscription : subscriptions.values())
   129→            topics.addAll(subscription.topics());
   130→
   131→        List<TopicPartition> allPartitions = new ArrayList<>();
   132→        for (String topic : topics) {
   133→            Integer numPartitionsForTopic = partitionsPerTopic.get(topic);
   134→            if (numPartitionsForTopic != null)
   135→                allPartitions.addAll(AbstractPartitionAssignor.partitions(topic, numPartitionsForTopic));
   136→        }
   137→        return allPartitions;
   138→    }
   139→
   140→    @Override
   141→    public String name() {
   142→        return ROUNDROBIN_ASSIGNOR_NAME;
   143→    }
   144→
   145→}
